---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Quick Start"
  description="Deploy your first app in 5 minutes"
  section="Getting Started"
>
  <p>
    This guide walks you through deploying a Dockerized application to a fresh VPS. By the end
    you will have a running app served over HTTPS with zero-downtime blue-green deploys.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Prerequisites:</strong> Shuttle installed, Docker running locally, a VPS with SSH
    access, and a domain pointing at your server's IP. See <a href="/docs/installation">Installation</a>
    if you haven't set up Shuttle yet.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1 — Initialize your project</h2>
  <p>
    Run <code>shuttle init</code> from the root of your application repository. It will ask
    a few questions and generate a <code>shuttle.yml</code> config file.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">cd my-app
shuttle init</code></pre>
  <p>The interactive wizard asks for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your application name</li>
    <li>Your domain (e.g. <code>my-app.example.com</code>)</li>
    <li>Your server address (e.g. <code>deploy@203.0.113.10</code>)</li>
    <li>Deploy strategy (blue-green, rolling, or swarm)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 2 — Edit shuttle.yml</h2>
  <p>
    Open the generated <code>shuttle.yml</code> and fill in the details for your application.
    Here is a typical config for a web app with a Postgres database:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com
server: deploy@203.0.113.10

build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green
  timeout: 120
  retain: 5
  auto_rollback: true

services:
  web:
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 6

accessories:
  postgres:
    preset: postgres
    env:
      POSTGRES_DB: my_app_production
      POSTGRES_USER: my_app
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: !secret DB_PASSWORD

env:
  clear:
    NODE_ENV: production
    PORT: "3000"
  secret:
    - DATABASE_URL

secrets:
  file: .shuttle.secrets

proxy:
  driver: caddy
  ssl: true</code></pre>
  <p>
    The <code>!secret</code> tag references an encrypted value from your secrets file.
    We will set that up in a moment.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3 — Set up secrets</h2>
  <p>
    Create your secrets file and add the values your application needs. Shuttle encrypts this
    file using AES-256-GCM so it is safe to commit to your repository.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash"># Set individual secrets
shuttle secrets set DB_PASSWORD "a-strong-password"
shuttle secrets set DATABASE_URL "postgres://my_app:a-strong-password@localhost/my_app_production"</code></pre>
  <p>
    This writes encrypted values to <code>.shuttle.secrets</code>. Add this file to git:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">git add .shuttle.secrets
git commit -m "chore: add shuttle secrets"</code></pre>

  <h2>Step 4 — Provision your server</h2>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle provision</code> bootstraps your VPS. It connects over SSH and installs
    Docker, Caddy, and configures the firewall. This is a one-time step per server.
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle provision</code></pre>
  <p>Provisioning takes 2–5 minutes. Shuttle will:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Update system packages</li>
    <li>Install Docker Engine and Docker Compose</li>
    <li>Install Caddy as the reverse proxy</li>
    <li>Configure UFW to allow ports 22, 80, and 443</li>
    <li>Create the <code>/opt/shuttle/my-app/</code> directory structure</li>
    <li>Set up the deploy user and SSH authorized keys</li>
    <li>Start accessories (Postgres in this case)</li>
    <li>Push your secrets to the server</li>
    <li>Verify Docker is healthy</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Step 5 — Deploy</h2>
  <p>
    Now deploy your application:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle deploy</code></pre>
  <p>Shuttle will walk through 12 steps:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Validate configuration</li>
    <li>Acquire deploy lock (prevents concurrent deploys)</li>
    <li>Build the Docker image locally: <code>shuttle/my-app:deploy-20240315-abc1234</code></li>
    <li>Save the image to a tarball</li>
    <li>Transfer the tarball to the server over SFTP</li>
    <li>Load the image on the server</li>
    <li>Start the new container on the green slot</li>
    <li>Run health checks against the new container</li>
    <li>Update Caddy to route traffic to the new container</li>
    <li>Stop the old container (blue slot)</li>
    <li>Prune old images (keeping the last <code>retain</code> tags)</li>
    <li>Release the deploy lock</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    If health checks fail, Shuttle automatically rolls back: Caddy is reverted to the previous
    slot and the failed container is stopped.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 6 — Visit your domain</h2>
  <p>
    Open <code>https://my-app.example.com</code> in your browser. Caddy will have obtained a
    Let's Encrypt certificate automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 7 — Check status</h2>
  <p>
    Verify your deployment at any time:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle status</code></pre>
  <p>
    This connects to the server and reports:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Active slot (blue or green) and container ID</li>
    <li>Current image tag</li>
    <li>Uptime of the running container</li>
    <li>Health check status</li>
    <li>Accessory container states</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Subsequent deploys</h2>
  <p>
    Every subsequent deploy is just:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle deploy</code></pre>
  <p>
    Or with a specific version tag:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle deploy --tag v1.2.0</code></pre>

  <h2>Rolling back</h2>
  <p>
    Roll back to the previous deploy instantly:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle rollback</code></pre>

